word_summaries_chapter_97:
  97:1:1:"The first word of verse (97:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. An accusative particle and object pronoun. The accusative particle belongs to a special group of words known as <i class=\"ab\">inna</i> and her sisters (<span class=\"at\">ان واخواتها</span>). The attached object pronoun is first person plural."
  97:1:2:"The second word of verse (97:1) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A verb, subject pronoun and object pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is first person plural. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn zāy lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ز ل</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">نا</span>) is an attached subject pronoun. The attached object pronoun is third person masculine singular."
  97:1:3:"The third word of verse (97:1) is a preposition."
  97:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (97:1) is a feminine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">lām yā lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ل ي ل</span>)."
  97:1:5:"The fifth word of verse (97:1) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf dāl rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق د ر</span>)."
  97:2:1:"The first word of verse (97:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and interrogative noun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  97:2:2:"The second word of verse (97:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dāl rā yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">د ر ي</span>). The attached object pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  97:2:3:"The third word of verse (97:2) is an interrogative noun."
  97:2:4:"The fourth word of verse (97:2) is a feminine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">lām yā lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ل ي ل</span>)."
  97:2:5:"The fifth word of verse (97:2) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf dāl rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق د ر</span>)."
  97:3:1:"The first word of verse (97:3) is a feminine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">lām yā lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ل ي ل</span>)."
  97:3:2:"The second word of verse (97:3) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf dāl rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق د ر</span>)."
  97:3:3:"The third word of verse (97:3) is an indefinite masculine singular noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā yā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ي ر</span>)."
  97:3:4:"The fourth word of verse (97:3) is a preposition."
  97:3:5:"The fifth word of verse (97:3) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām fā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ف</span>)."
  97:3:6:"The sixth word of verse (97:3) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn hā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ه ر</span>)."
  97:4:1:"The first word of verse (97:4) is a form V imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person feminine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn zāy lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ز ل</span>)."
  97:4:2:"The second word of verse (97:4) is a masculine plural noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">mīm lām kāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">م ل ك</span>)."
  97:4:3:"The third word of verse (97:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and noun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The noun is masculine and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā wāw ḥā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر و ح</span>)."
  97:4:4:"The fourth word of verse (97:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and object pronoun. The attached object pronoun is third person feminine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  97:4:5:"The fifth word of verse (97:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">bi</i> is usually translated as \"with\" or \"by\". The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza dhāl nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ذ ن</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  97:4:6:"The sixth word of verse (97:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā bā bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ب ب</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person masculine plural."
  97:4:7:"The seventh word of verse (97:4) is a preposition."
  97:4:8:"The eighth word of verse (97:4) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">kāf lām lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ك ل ل</span>)."
  97:4:9:"The ninth word of verse (97:4) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza mīm rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ م ر</span>)."
  97:5:1:"The first word of verse (97:5) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">sīn lām mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">س ل م</span>)."
  97:5:2:"The second word of verse (97:5) is a third person feminine singular personal pronoun."
  97:5:3:"The third word of verse (97:5) is a preposition."
  97:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (97:5) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṭā lām ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ط ل ع</span>)."
  97:5:5:"The fifth word of verse (97:5) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">fā jīm rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ف ج ر</span>)."